  "why": "The paper goes beyond merely reporting failures: it analyzes where and how failures occur in relation to model internals and statistical patterns. The authors link discovered adversarial and backdoor inputs to differences in internal activations (gates, hidden states) and show how coverage metrics (BC, SC, TC) reveal distinct temporal and stepwise activation patterns. They also use coverage-time and per-feature coverage analyses to explain which input features or time steps drive model behaviour (e.g., sensitive words in IMDB, rows of pixels in MNIST). However, the paper does not consistently trace failures to deeper root causes such as corrupted or biased training data or spurious dataset features; the diagnostics remain at the level of characterizing failure patterns and relating them to internal activation/coverage behaviour rather than identifying underlying dataset-level or training-process causes. This corresponds to the “Medium” level: partial diagnostic insight via model internals and statistical failure patterns, without full root-cause attributions.",
